board-response.response:
{
  "role": "account-manager",
  "department": "client-services",
  "scores": {
    "philosophy_depth": 6,
    "handoff_specificity": 8,
    "anti_pattern_quality": 1,
    "ai_deployment_clarity": 6,
    "story_portal_relevance": 6
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 6,
      "finding": "The six principles are high-level and read like generic platitudes rather than concrete guidance for this role.",
      "example_rewrite": "**Proactive Engagement:** Initiate monthly business reviews using CRM analytics to surface potential issues two weeks before renewal conversations."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 1,
      "finding": "There is no anti-pattern section defined. The role template omits any description of what behaviours or traps to avoid.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Anti-Patterns\n1. **Inbox Only:** Waiting for client outreach instead of scheduling proactive check-ins.\n2. **Solo Play:** Handling feedback without looping in Product or Support for resolutions.\n3. **Statue Syndrome:** Never updating CRM status leading to data blind spots.\n4. **Renewal Rush:** Leaving negotiations to the last week and risking churn.\n5. **Feature Dump:** Overwhelming clients with all product features instead of targeted value discussion."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 6,
      "finding": "AI tasks are broadly described; triggers, outputs, and success criteria for AI assistants are not explicitly defined.",
      "example_rewrite": "### AI Assistant Tasks\n- Every Monday at 8 AM, AI compiles a 1-page account health report from CRM and flags scores < 70%.\n- On meeting completion, AI drafts follow-up emails and action-item lists within 30 minutes.\n- AI monitors support ticket trends daily and alerts AM for any 3+ critical issues in 24 hours."
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 6,
      "finding": "The Story Portal appendix lists partner types and themes but lacks actionable story deliverables or integration points with the portal system.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Story Portal Tasks\n- For Festival Partners: Upload a ‘Partnership Journey’ story card after each event, tagging outcomes to Story Portal milestones.\n- For Community Sponsors: Draft quarterly impact highlight posts in the Portal’s ‘Sponsor Spotlight’ section.\n- For Platform Partners: Submit integration case studies with screenshots into the ‘Tech Integrations’ module."
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Add a dedicated anti-patterns section with 3–5 role-specific traps to avoid, ensuring clear guidance on what NOT to do."
}

```json
{
  "role": "account-manager",
  "department": "client-services",
  "scores": {
    "philosophy_depth": 3,
    "handoff_specificity": 3,
    "anti_pattern_quality": 1,
    "ai_deployment_clarity": 4,
    "story_portal_relevance": 4
  },
  "findings": [
    {
      "dimension": "philosophy_depth",
      "score": 3,
      "finding": "All 6 principles are generic sales/AM platitudes that could appear in any account management textbook. 'Relationship First: Trust enables everything' and 'Growth Through Service: Expansion follows value' are empty aphorisms with no Story Portal specificity, no behavioral guidance, and no decision-making weight. They tell an AI agent nothing about how to behave when values conflict — e.g., when a festival partner wants a feature that contradicts product direction. None of the principles reference the empathy-driven, story-focused, community mission context that Story Portal operates in.",
      "example_rewrite": "| **Mission-Anchored Partnership** | Story Portal clients are community advocates, not revenue targets. Every engagement decision — cadence, framing, expansion pitch — must reinforce their empathy mission, not just our retention metrics. If a renewal conversation feels transactional, stop and reframe around impact. | | **Churn Signals Are Stories, Not Data Points** | A drop in NPS from a Festival Partner isn't a metric to manage — it's a signal that their community story isn't landing. Dig into the narrative before escalating to Head of Client Services. | | **Internal Advocacy Has a Cost** | When you represent a client's request to Product or Sales, you are spending organizational credibility. Be selective, be specific, and always attach client evidence — not just sentiment. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "handoff_specificity",
      "score": 3,
      "finding": "Handoffs are critically vague on both sides. 'Receives From: Sales → Closed clients' is not an artifact — it names a category of people, not a document, system record, or structured data package. 'Delivers To: Sales → Expansion opportunities' could mean a verbal mention in Slack or a formal briefing document. An AI agent cannot act on these. There is also no specification of format, trigger condition, or required fields for any handoff. The collaboration table lists 'Client Success Manager' as a collaborator but this role does not appear in the Handoffs section at all, creating a gap.",
      "example_rewrite": "| Receives From | Artifact | Format | Trigger | Required Fields | | Sales | Client Onboarding Handoff Package | CRM record + PDF summary | Deal marked Closed-Won | Contact map, contract value, stated goals, known risks, Sales rep notes | | Support | Issue Resolution Update | CRM case closure note | Case closed or escalated | Issue description, resolution, client sentiment score, AM action required Y/N | | Delivers To | Artifact | Format | Trigger | | Sales | Expansion Opportunity Brief | 1-page structured brief in CRM | Client expresses interest OR AM identifies upsell signal | Fields: client name, opportunity type, estimated value, client quote, recommended next step |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "anti_pattern_quality",
      "score": 1,
      "finding": "There is no Anti-Patterns section in this role file. The template standard explicitly requires 3-5 role-specific anti-patterns. The DO/DON'T boundary list in Core Identity partially covers boundary violations but reads as domain ownership rules, not behavioral failure modes. It does not identify how an AM specifically fails — e.g., over-promising during renewals, becoming a complaint relay instead of an advocate, or confusing activity (touchpoint count) with health (relationship quality). An AI agent has no failure mode awareness from this file.",
      "example_rewrite": "## Anti-Patterns\n\n| Anti-Pattern | Why It Fails | Correct Behavior |\n|---|---|---|\n| **Touchpoint Theater** | Logging check-in calls without surfacing actionable insights creates the appearance of engagement while missing real churn signals. | Every touchpoint must produce one CRM update with a health signal change or confirmed status. |\n| **Complaint Relay** | Passing client frustrations to Product or Support verbatim without AM interpretation wastes organizational capital and positions AM as a messenger, not an advocate. | Translate client complaints into structured feedback with business impact before escalating. |\n| **Renewal Ambush** | Initiating renewal conversation fewer than 60 days before expiry without prior health assessment forces negotiation under pressure. | Renewal strategy must be drafted 90 days out with health score, risk flags, and value review completed before client contact. |\n| **Expansion Before Value** | Pitching upsell to a client whose core use case is unresolved damages trust and accelerates churn. | Confirm satisfaction score ≥ threshold and at least one documented value realization before any expansion conversation. |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "ai_deployment_clarity",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "The Iteration Protocol exists and is structurally correct, but the AI/human division of labor is described at the category level only — 'AI assists with analysis, AI prepares materials' — with no specification of what analysis, what materials, what format, or what triggers AI action versus human action. The Context Requirements section contains literal placeholder text '[Context item 1]' and '[Context item 2]' and the Required Skills table has no entries, only a format note. This means an AI agent loading this role cannot determine what context to load, what documents to prepare before a client meeting, or what constitutes a complete preparation step. The STOP points in workflows are present but their human-approval criteria are undefined.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Required Context\n- [ ] client-account-record.md — CRM summary for active account including health score, contract value, renewal date, open issues\n- [ ] story-portal-product-updates.md — Current feature releases and roadmap items relevant to client's stated goals\n- [ ] renewal-history.md — Prior renewal terms, negotiation notes, pricing concessions granted\n\n### AI Action Triggers\n| Trigger | AI Action | Output Format | Human Review Required |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Meeting scheduled T-48h | Pull CRM account summary, draft agenda, flag open issues | Meeting Brief (structured doc) | Yes — AM approves before sending |\n| NPS score received | Compare to prior score, flag if delta > -10, draft follow-up message | Health Signal Update in CRM + draft email | Yes — AM reviews sentiment framing |\n| Renewal date T-90 | Generate renewal readiness checklist, draft value review deck outline | Renewal Prep Package | Yes — AM validates before client contact |"
    },
    {
      "dimension": "story_portal_relevance",
      "score": 4,
      "finding": "The Story Portal appendix names four client types (Festival Partners, Community Sponsors, Platform Partners, Advocates) but provides no differentiated engagement guidance per client type. All four types are listed with one-line labels and no behavioral difference in how an AM should approach them. The Relationship Themes table ('Mission alignment: Shared empathy goals') repeats the same generic philosophy problem — it names themes but provides no tactical guidance. An AI agent cannot determine from this section how to frame a renewal conversation with a Festival Partner differently from a Platform Partner, or what a healthy vs. at-risk Advocate relationship looks like in Story Portal's context.",
      "example_rewrite": "### Client Type Engagement Matrix\n\n| Client Type | Relationship Driver | Renewal Lever | Expansion Signal | Churn Warning Sign |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Festival Partners** | Event success and community visibility | Demonstrate measurable story reach from prior event cycle | Partner asks about multi-event or year-round presence | Decreased engagement in event planning calls; late responses to logistics |\n| **Community Sponsors** | Impact credibility and mission alignment | Share community stories directly attributable to their sponsorship | Sponsor mentions new internal CSR initiative | Sponsor shifts language from 'partnership' to 'vendor' |\n| **Platform Partners** | Integration reliability and developer experience | API uptime metrics and integration adoption data | Partner requests additional endpoint access or co-marketing | Declining API call volume; unresolved integration tickets aging > 14 days |\n| **Advocates** | Personal recognition and community leadership | Highlight their individual impact stories in platform communications | Advocate begins referring others unprompted | Advocate stops posting; disengages from community channels |"
    }
  ],
  "top_improvement": "Add a complete Anti-Patterns section — this role file has zero anti-patterns, which is the single largest gap. An AI agent operating as a Hybrid Account Manager with no failure mode awareness will default to generic helpful behavior, miss churn signals, and violate collaboration boundaries without any self-correction mechanism. Draft 4 role-specific anti-patterns (Touchpoint Theater, Complaint Relay, Renewal Ambush, Expansion Before Value) before addressing any other section."
}
```
